<div class="thumbinner" style="width:295px;"><a href="/wiki/File:IE_expansion.png" class="image" title="Map of Indo European migrations from ca. 4000 to 1000 BC according to the Kurgan model.  The Anatolian migration (indicated with a dotted arrow) could have taken place either across the Caucasus or across the Balkans.  The purple area corresponds to the assumed Urheimat (Samara culture, Sredny Stog culture). The red area corresponds to the area which may have been settled by Indo-European-speaking peoples up to ca. 2500 BC, and the orange area by 1000 BC."><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5a/IE_expansion.png/293px-IE_expansion.png" width="293" height="179" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:IE_expansion.png" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
Map of Indo European migrations from ca. 4000 to 1000 BC according to the Kurgan model. The Anatolian migration (indicated with a dotted arrow) could have taken place either across the Caucasus or across the Balkans. The purple area corresponds to the assumed <i><a href="/wiki/Urheimat" title="Urheimat">Urheimat</a></i> (<a href="/wiki/Samara_culture" title="Samara culture">Samara culture</a>, <a href="/wiki/Sredny_Stog_culture" title="Sredny Stog culture">Sredny Stog culture</a>). The red area corresponds to the area which may have been settled by Indo-European-speaking peoples up to ca. 2500 BC, and the orange area by 1000 BC.</div>
